        body: 'A business health score is a composite metric that blends multiple performance indicators into a single number, typically scaled from zero to one hundred. The specific inputs and their weights vary by platform, but most health scores incorporate revenue trend relative to historical baselines, gross margin percentage, inventory turnover rate, customer transaction frequency, average transaction value, and operational metrics like refund rates and void percentages. The score is not a grade in the academic sense. A score of seventy-five does not mean your business is failing any more than a resting heart rate of seventy-five means you are unhealthy. Context determines interpretation. A score that has been stable at seventy-five for six months reflects a business in steady state. The same score following three months at eighty-five signals a decline worth investigating. Weekly patterns are particularly revealing because they smooth out the daily noise that makes single-day scores unreliable. A Monday score might dip because foot traffic is naturally lower, not because anything is wrong. A Sunday spike might reflect weekend shopping patterns rather than genuine improvement. By looking at full-week averages and week-over-week changes, managers filter out cyclical noise and focus on the meaningful signals. AskBiz health scores are designed to reflect the overall trajectory of your business across multiple dimensions simultaneously. The platform highlights which specific input metrics are driving score changes, so you always know whether a dip is margin-driven, volume-driven, or reflecting shifts in customer behavior.'
